Latin America in the fight against the coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not meet this crisis decisively, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, political reactions in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and made the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, unfortunately, downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose a populist and divisive policy amidst the tragedy.
Latin America's top priority must be to minimize the number of deaths during the pandemic.
Politicians must focus on improving health systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily utilizing idle infrastructure like hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
Moreover, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other crucial resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in contrast to US President Donald Trump’s callous decision to freeze around 500 million dollars in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – so that we can finally bring an end to the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has Latin American domestic production been interrupted, but countries there also suffer from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to lack of tourism, fewer foreign remittances, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with the decline in demand.
To prevent this, bold measures are needed to protect household incomes.
This means transfers to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief for businesses is also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay wages and benefits protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Such support is crucial for a quick economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the wave of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at that point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – would be endangered.
Many companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon turn into a solvency problem.
Tax relief, payment deferrals, and subsidized credits will not be enough.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees by governments to ensure that banks continue to lend, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and managed state banks can play a leading role here.
All in all, while the measures will vary by country, extraordinary budget resources will likely be necessary everywhere to accelerate recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening health risks.
The problem is that fiscal space in Latin America today is even tighter than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, budget pressures in lower-priority areas need to be eased through budget adjustments.
There is the risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, which can be mitigated by government promises to correct higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, external support for households and balance sheets will be urgently needed, especially for small and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and states run larger deficits, the countries' current account balances are likely to deteriorate as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the biggest reversals in the history of financial markets – exacerbates the problem even further.
The resulting currency devaluations could have destabilizing effects.
In many economies in the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive much more external support.
Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
It must address the short-term currency and budget needs of countries and continue to support their economies, which, given the highly uncertain duration of this crisis, require further assistance.
For this, it needs more resources and the ability to pay them out quickly.
Latin American governments should jointly call for a new issuance of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights (SDRs), which should amount to one trillion SDRs.
While SDRs are allocated to member countries based on their IMF quotas, an unequal allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the supervision of the Fund.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity through immediately doubling the volume of new credit arrangements to cover the upcoming strong credit demand.
And finally, since traditional IMF credit programs are not approved in time, the fund must improve access to low-threshold tools with quick disbursement – such as its Rapid Financing Instrument – or initiate new pandemic-specific credit facilities.
Central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
At home, central banks must use all available instruments and create new ones if necessary to supply financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
Finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) like the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net lending in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide additional budget support.
In extraordinary circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending could be supplemented by a debt reduction.
The MDBs should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of the COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role here.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – not populism or demagoguery.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-won citizen rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and demonstrate what it can offer to citizens.
